\section{Required Equations}
  
The Intensity of radiation in the presence of an absorber is, \cite{Tokmakoff}
\begin{equation}
	I = I_0 e^{-N\alpha\L}
\end{equation}
Where N is number density of the absorbing molecule, L the length of the absorbing region, and $\alpha$ the cross section of absorbtion.
Tokmakoff also gives for a single spectal line,
\begin{equation}
	\alpha = \frac{h\nu}{c} B
\end{equation}	
 Where $\nu$ is the frequency, and $B$ is the Einstein $B$ coefficient. HITRAN gives us the Einstein $A$ coefficent, which is related to $B$
 (at equilibrium) by \cite{Mourya}
 \begin{equation}
 	A = \frac{8\pi h \nu^3}{c^3} B
 	\end{equation}
 So
 \begin{equation}
 	\alpha = \frac{c^2}{8\pi\nu^2} A
 \end{equation}
Of course we need the spectral lines for each absorber, labelled $M$, so
\begin{equation}
	I  = I_0 e^{-L\left(\sum_M N_m\ \sum_\nu \frac{c^2}{8\pi\nu^23} \right)}
\end{equation}

The input intensity is the Planck Radiation Law  of EM emission from a surface at temperature T, \cite{Brit1}

\begin{equation}
	I_0(\nu) = \frac{8\pi h \nu^5}{c^4}\frac{1}{e^\frac{-h\nu}{kT}} -1
\end{equation}

The width of the spectra line is commonly approximated as a Lorenzian, due to Natural and Collusional broadaning. \cite{KW} In fact the Lorenz shape estimate the tail of absorption, and
is often cut off at the edges, but we will not do that here. In HITRAN \cite{HITRANUnits} units, we lose the factor of $4\pi^2$ and the line width is proportional to the pressure $P$,
$\Gamma= P\gamma$, of the line width in table 1.

\begin{equation}
 \phi(\nu) = \frac {\Gamma}{(\nu-\nu_0)^2 + \Gamma^2} 
\end{equation}

So now we have the absorption equation for surface tempature $T$ and Pressure $P$ at each height, so need a model of earths surface temperature and latitude $\theta$, and atmospheric 
pressure at height $h$, to complete our input equations.


